                    <h2>Letter F</h2>
                    <p>The letter 'F' in ASL is similar to the 'okay' gesture, with a few distinctive differences that
                        are key for clear communication. It is formed by creating a circle with the thumb and index
                        finger while the other fingers remain extended.</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Hand Open Start:</strong> Begin with your hand open and palm facing towards the
                            person you are communicating with, fingers spread slightly.</li>
                        <li><strong>Create Circle:</strong> Touch the tip of your thumb to the tip of your index finger.
                            The touch should be gentle but firm, creating a clear and visible circle or 'O' shape.</li>
                        <li><strong>Extend Other Fingers:</strong> Keep your middle, ring, and pinky fingers straight
                            and spread out. They should be elevated, making sure they do not droop, to maintain the
                            integrity of the 'F' sign.</li>
                        <li><strong>Thumb and Index Finger Position:</strong> Verify that the thumb and index finger are
                            not pinching too tight or too loose. The circle should be round and the size consistent,
                            resembling the letter 'O' from the side view.</li>
                        <li><strong>Hand Orientation:</strong> Ensure your hand is oriented correctly with your palm
                            facing forward or slightly towards yourself, which helps in differentiating the 'F' from
                            other similar signs.</li>
                    </ul>
                    <p>Practicing the 'F' sign is essential as it not only represents the letter but is also used in
                        various other signs in ASL. Focus on the roundness of the circle and the position of the other
                        fingers to clearly convey the letter 'F'.</p>
