                <h2>Letter G</h2>
                <p>The 'G' in ASL is indicated by a pointed index finger, with the rest of the fingers curled into the
                    palm and the thumb extended across. It’s a precise gesture that requires attention to finger
                    positioning.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Start with your hand open, palm facing down towards the
                        ground.</li>
                    <li><strong>Index Finger Extension:</strong> Extend your index finger straight out from the palm,
                        keeping it isolated and pointing directly forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curling Other Fingers:</strong> Curl your middle, ring, and pinky fingers into your
                        palm. Ensure they're held tightly against your palm to avoid confusion with other signs.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Position your thumb so it extends outwards, lying flat and
                        perpendicular to the index finger. The thumb should not touch any other fingers, maintaining the
                        clear shape of the 'G'.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Keep the 'G' sign clear by maintaining the index finger fully
                        extended and the thumb outstretched, not tucked in or bent. The hand should be steady and the
                        sign held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Repeat the formation of the 'G' sign multiple times, checking in a mirror to ensure accuracy. This
                    letter is essential for many words in ASL, and its correct formation is important for effective
                    communication.</p>
